Normalization is an important preprocessing step that helps machine learning and deep learning models learn more effectively.
 How does normalization work?
Normalization is the process of scaling pixel values so that all images are on a similar numerical range. Since image pixels are typically stored as integers from 0 to 255, normalization converts them to a smaller range, usually 0 to 1 or -1 to 1.
Why Normalize an ASL Dataset?
For ASL, normalization provides several benefits:
1. Faster Model Training
Neural networks converge more quickly when input features are on a similar scale.
2. Improved Accuracy
Normalized images help prevent certain pixels from dominating the learning process.
3. Better Gradient Descent Performance
Large pixel values can cause unstable gradients during training.
4. Consistency Across Images
ASL datasets often contain images captured under different lighting conditions. Normalization reduces the impact of brightness variations.

Common Normalization Methods
Method 1: Min-Max Normalization
Scale pixel values to the range [0,1].

Method 2: Standardization (Z-Score)
Subtract the mean and divide by the standard deviation.


Why Use Augmentation for ASL?
Benefits include:
•	Reduces overfitting 
•	Improves model robustness 
•	Simulates real-world variations 
•	Increases effective dataset size 
•	Helps the model recognize signs under different conditions
