For an ASL hand-sign recognition project, augmentation is typically applied only to the training set, while the validation and test sets remain unchanged so that model performance is evaluated on real, unmodified images.

Why transfer learning works well for ASL
1.	Lower data requirement
A pretrained model already knows how to detect edges, shapes, textures, and hand-like patterns, so you need fewer labeled ASL images.
2.	Faster training
You train only a small classification head (and optionally fine-tune later layers), reducing training time significantly.
3.	Better accuracy
Transfer learning often outperforms training from scratch on medium-sized ASL datasets.
4.	Reduced overfitting
The pretrained features provide a strong starting point, which helps the model generalize better.



